# Type Safety Rules

**Quick reference:** No `as string`/`as number`/`as boolean` — branded types are already their base type. No double-cast `as unknown as T`. No `Partial<T>` in production. No `{ ...obj, field }` spread-to-override on domain types. No `enum`, `for...in`, default exports, `Object.assign`, nested ternaries. No `!` non-null assertions.

## Branded Type Cast Removal

Branded types use intersection: `Brand<T, B> = T & { __brand: B }`. A `RelativePath` IS a `string`. A `TokenCount` IS a `number`. Casting to the base type strips the brand and adds noise.

### `as string` — remove the cast

```typescript
// before (lint error)
const p = file.path as string;
matchesGlob(p, pattern as string);
(a.path as string).localeCompare(b.path as string);

// after
const p = file.path;
matchesGlob(p, pattern);
a.path.localeCompare(b.path);
```

Branded strings support all `String.prototype` methods directly. Functions accepting `string` also accept branded strings.

### `as number` — remove the cast

```typescript
// before (lint error)
const t = f.estimatedTokens as number;
const total = files.reduce((s, f) => s + (f.estimatedTokens as number), 0);

// after
const t = f.estimatedTokens;
const total = files.reduce((s, f) => s + f.estimatedTokens, 0);
```

Arithmetic, comparisons, and `Math.*` functions work directly on branded numbers. The result type is `number` which is correct for derived values.

### `as boolean` — use a type guard

```typescript
// before (lint error)
const active = value as boolean;

// after
const active = Boolean(value);
// or
if (typeof value === "boolean") { ... }
```

## Double-Cast `as unknown as T`

Banned everywhere except `open-database.ts` (the single adapter boundary).

```typescript
// before (lint error)
const result = rawData as unknown as MyInterface;

// after — use a typed adapter function
function adaptRawData(raw: ExternalType): MyInterface {
  return {
    field1: raw.field1,
    field2: raw.field2,
  };
}
```

If bridging an untyped FFI boundary, isolate the cast in a single adapter file and add an ESLint override section for that file only.

## Object Literal Type Assertions

Banned by `consistent-type-assertions` with `objectLiteralTypeAssertions: "never"`.

```typescript
// before (lint error)
const config = { timeout: 5000, retries: 3 } as Config;

// after — use type annotation
const config: Config = { timeout: 5000, retries: 3 };
```

The annotation provides compile-time structural checking. The assertion silences it.

## Non-Null Assertion `!`

Banned by `@typescript-eslint/no-non-null-assertion`.

```typescript
// before (lint error)
const name = node.name!.getText(sf);
const first = items[0]!;

// after — use optional chaining + fallback
const name = node.name?.getText(sf) ?? "";

// or — use a null guard
if (items.length === 0) { return []; }
const first = items[0];
```

If a value is structurally guaranteed to exist (e.g., array index after length check), TypeScript's control flow analysis narrows the type automatically.

## Spread-to-Override on Domain Types

Not enforced by a lint rule (ESLint AST cannot distinguish domain objects from accumulators), but enforced by code review and this rule.

```typescript
// avoid in production — hides field evolution
const updated: SelectedFile = { ...file, tier: next, estimatedTokens: newTokens };

// prefer — explicit construction breaks at compile time when type evolves
const updated: SelectedFile = {
  path: file.path,
  language: file.language,
  estimatedTokens: newTokens,
  relevanceScore: file.relevanceScore,
  tier: next,
};
```

**Exceptions (spread is acceptable):**

- Reduce accumulators with file-local types (e.g., `StripperState` in `comment-stripper.ts`)
- Test factories using `Partial<T>` (tests are exempt from `Partial` ban)

## `Partial<T>` in Production (core/pipeline only)

Banned by `no-restricted-syntax` in `core/` and `pipeline/`.

```typescript
// before (lint error in core/pipeline)
function update(base: Config, overrides: Partial<Config>): Config {
  return { ...base, ...overrides };
}

// after — explicit parameter type
function update(base: Config, newTimeout: Milliseconds): Config {
  return {
    timeout: newTimeout,
    retries: base.retries,
    endpoint: base.endpoint,
  };
}
```

If a function truly needs flexible overrides, define a separate narrower type listing only the mutable fields.

## TypeScript `enum`

Banned globally. Use `as const` objects following the existing pattern in `core/types/enums.ts`:

```typescript
// before (lint error)
enum TaskClass { Feature = "feature", Bugfix = "bugfix" }

// after
const TASK_CLASS = { FEATURE: "feature", BUGFIX: "bugfix" } as const;
type TaskClass = (typeof TASK_CLASS)[keyof typeof TASK_CLASS];
```

## `for...in`

Banned globally. Iterates inherited properties and has surprising behavior.

```typescript
// before (lint error)
for (const key in obj) { ... }

// after
for (const key of Object.keys(obj)) { ... }
// or
for (const [key, value] of Object.entries(obj)) { ... }
```

## Default Exports

Banned globally. Named exports are grep-friendly and refactor-safe.

```typescript
// before (lint error)
export default class Foo { ... }

// after
export class Foo { ... }
```

## `Object.assign`

Banned globally. Mutates the first argument.

```typescript
// before (lint error)
const merged = Object.assign({}, a, b);

// after
const merged = { ...a, ...b };
```

## Nested Ternaries

Banned globally. Extract to a function or dispatch map.

```typescript
// before (lint error)
const label = x > 10 ? "high" : x > 5 ? "medium" : "low";

// after — dispatch function
function classifyValue(x: number): string {
  if (x > 10) { return "high"; }
  if (x > 5) { return "medium"; }
  return "low";
}
```

## Layer Exemptions

| Rule | Production | Tests | open-database.ts |
|------|-----------|-------|------------------|
| `as string` / `as number` / `as boolean` | Error | Off | Error |
| Double-cast `as X as Y` | Error | Off | Off |
| `Partial<T>` | Error (core/pipeline) | Off | N/A |
| `!` non-null assertion | Error | Off | Error |
| `consistent-type-assertions` | Error | Off | Error |
| `enum`, `for...in`, default export | Error | Error | Error |
| `Object.assign`, nested ternary | Error | Error | Error |
